  m_Script: {fileID: 11500000, guid: 889faa658c7b2c94ea4fff939bf8022e, type: 3}
  m_Name: DialogNPCArmourer
  m_EditorClassIdentifier: 
  Name: Patrizio
  Icon: {fileID: 7416670922274956215, guid: 67e11902f9a599344b5dc2f4b5a33db5, type: 3}
  HasInteraction: 0
  interactionType: 0
  Greeting: Patrick The Armourer
  Day1Dialog:
  - "Ah, a new face. Careful where you step, boy \u2014 the forge is hotter than
    the sun.\nThe Turks thunder on us with their guns, yet we still fire back. Every
    night, boats slip across from Birgu \u2014 powder, matchlocks, hoops of Greek
    fire. Without them, my hammers would be useless.\nSee this barrel? Enough gunpowder
    for one night only."
  Day2FirstTimeDialog:
  - "Look at the ravelin, boy. The Janissaries took it yesterday \u2014 we lost good
    men holding it.\nI patch armour for those who limped back, mend muskets that
    fired until barrels glowed.\nWe throw hoops of Greek fire down the walls, but
    for every Turk we burn, two more climb the ditch."
  Day2MetBeforeDialog:
  - "Remember the ravelin I showed you? Taken yesterday. Our men held it as long
    as they could.\nI\u2019ve been up all night reforging blades and mending muskets.\nEven
    with iron in my hands, it feels like the fort itself is bleeding."
  Day3FirstTimeDialog:
  - "Hear that roar, boy? Dragut himself arrived with new cannon at Gallows\u2019
    Point.\nStone falls like rain inside the fort \u2014 we barely patch the walls
    before they crack again.\nI sharpen swords, mend armour, and still the powder
    runs low. Every shot we fire brings another Turkish counter."
  Day3MetBeforeDialog:
  - "I told you yesterday the walls were cracking \u2014 now see Dragut\u2019s guns
    pounding us from Gallows\u2019 Point.\nEven my hammer shakes with the blasts.\nAnd
    yet, La Valette sends more men across the water at night. Volunteers to stand
    and die beside us.\nI mend their armour\u2026 and hope they survive long enough
    to use it."
  Day4FirstTimeDialog:
  - "The assaults continue, boy. Wave after wave hurled at our walls \u2014 yet still
    we hold.\nBodies fill the ditch, stones tumble, and my forge works nonstop.\nEach
    repaired sword or helm might save a man\u2019s life\u2026 or not.\nBut we fight,
    because the Grand Master demands St. Elmo stand."
  Day4MetBeforeDialog:
  - "Yesterday, we barely held. Today, again, the Turks crash against our walls.\nI
    mend every sword, every dented helm, every cracked musket.\nThe fort is bleeding
    stone and blood, yet still it breathes.\nWe hammer and forge, and pray it\u2019s
    enough for another day."
  Day5FirstTimeDialog:
  - Tomorrow may be our last stand. Dragut oversees every shot, and we have only
    a fraction of the weapons we need. Every cannon, musket, and hoop of Greek fire
    I repair could be the difference between life and death.
  Day5MetBeforeDialog:
  - "This is it. You\u2019ve seen repairs, cannon care, muskets sharpened. Around
    half the defenders are dead. Every weapon might decide who survives when St.
    Elmo falls. Courage and preparation hang in the balance"
  dayNumber: 1
  metOnday1: 0
